<subSubSection id="C31D6510FFBFFFDDFF4FCF042C49F8CC" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BB8369BFFBFFFDDFF4FCF042C50FD99" blockId="21.[151,1306,466,585]" box="[151,1027,562,585]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBFFFDDFF4FCF042946FD99" box="[151,277,562,585]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBFFFDDFF4FCF042946FD99" box="[151,277,562,585]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Orthostolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: species 
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBFFFDDFEAECF0429CDFD99" box="[374,414,562,585]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="7.0" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="5.0">5–9</number>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EF964B6AFFBFFFDDFE74CF042AA7FD99" author="Sharp" box="[428,756,562,585]" pageId="21" pageNumber="28" refString="Sharp, D. &amp; Scott, H. (1908) Coleoptera 3. In: D. Sharp (Ed.), Fauna Hawaiiensis: being the land-fauna of the Hawaiian Islands. Cambridge University Press, London, pp. 435 - 508." type="book chapter" year="1908">
Sharp &amp; Scott, 
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBFFFDDFD8ACF042AD8FD99" box="[594,651,562,585]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="1908.0">1908</number>
: 
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBFFFDDFD4DCF042AA7FD99" box="[661,756,562,585]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="455.0" valueMax="456.0" valueMin="454.0">454–456</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) removed to 
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBFFFDDFC5ACF042BAFFD99" box="[898,1020,562,585]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Apetasimus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBFFFDDFC5ACF042BAFFD99" box="[898,1020,562,585]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Apetasimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB8369BFFBFFFDDFF4FCF4C2C48FC8C" blockId="21.[151,1437,634,2020]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Diagnosis: Size medium to large, 4.5–7.7 mm L; 1.5–3.0 mm W. Size and color highly variable within species. Males usually dark brown to nearly black, dark markings weakly contrasting; females pale yellow to dark brown often with strongly contrasting dark markings similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBFFFDDFC17CFFC2CC6FD34" authority="Sharp" authorityName="Sharp" box="[975,1173,714,740]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Eupetinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBFFFDDFC17CFFC2C17FD33" box="[975,1092,714,739]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Eupetinus</emphasis>
Sharp
</taxonomicName>
, most conspicuous on scutellum and abdomen. Pronotum with U-shaped area of anterior directed setae at anterior margin behind head. Antennal club compact, 
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBFFFDDFE25CE2C2A58FCE4" box="[509,523,794,820]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="9.0">9</number>
th antennomere transverse. Microsculpture of dorsum variable among species and within species, from granulate to fine lines, never obsolete and glabrous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB8369BFFBFFFDDFF1ECE5C28A0FBA4" blockId="21.[151,1437,634,2020]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Description: Eyes small, facets fine; temple short, acute, postgenae forming obtuse angle with occiput. Antennal grooves convergent, medial and lateral margins distinct. Antennal club elongate, antennomere nine transverse. Labrum with two pairs dorsal macrosetae; medial tooth broadly rounded; laterally sinuate to bisinuate, each side with two distinct patches of ventromarginal setae, a smaller patch of short setae adjacent to medial projection and a larger, longer patch before the lateral angle. Mandibles each with two apical teeth and three to six stout subapical teeth. Third labial palpomere subtransvers to weakly elongate, narrowed slightly distally.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB8369BFFBFFFDDFF1EC9B429F9FAEC" blockId="21.[151,1437,634,2020]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Prothorax transverse. Lateral margins smoothly curved or recurved at posterior angle; smooth to weakly crenulate, marginal setae elongate, moderately dense for entire length. Pronotum with area of anterior directed setae behind at anterior margin behind head; remaining setae directed posteriorly. Prosternal process greatly expanded posterad of coxae, 
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBFFFDDFE2AC9CC2A4DFAC4" box="[498,542,1274,1300]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">
2– 
<date id="FFB9105BFFBFFFDDFDC9C9CC2A4DFAC4" box="[529,542,1274,1300]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">3</date>
</number>
x minimum width between coxae; little recurved dorsad posterad of coxae; broadly curved at apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB8369BFFBFFFDDFF1EC87C2960F9FC" blockId="21.[151,1437,634,2020]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Elytra 
<date id="FFB9105BFFBFFFDDFEC1C87C2965FAB4" box="[281,310,1354,1380]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBFFFDDFEC1C87C2974FAB4" box="[281,295,1354,1380]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="2.0">2</number>
x
</date>
as long as wide or less; lateral margin greater than 
<date id="FFB9105BFFBFFFDDFC63C87C2B8BFAB4" box="[955,984,1354,1380]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBFFFDDFC63C87C2B9AFAB4" box="[955,969,1354,1380]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="2.0">2</number>
x
</date>
width of marginal bead, widest near humeral angle. Punctures of elytra coarse, forming distinct striae; striae 
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBFFFDDFBDCC8442C63FA5C" box="[1028,1072,1394,1420]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="4.5" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="1.0">1–8</number>
nearly regular, 
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBFFFDDFB2AC8442D53FA5C" box="[1266,1280,1394,1420]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="9.0">9</number>
and 
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBFFFDDFA98C8442D0EFA5C" box="[1344,1373,1394,1420]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="10.0">10</number>
with punctures reduced, and increasingly more irregular toward elytral margin. Interstices of elytra slightly raised; wide with multiple confused rows of setae; interstices 
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBFFFDDFCD7C8F42B4DFA0C" box="[783,798,1474,1500]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="6.0">6</number>
and 
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBFFFDDFC8EC8F42B37FA0C" box="[854,868,1474,1500]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="7.0">7</number>
dilated near middle, often extended distally and/ or proximally. Surface of elytra nearly even to distinctly uneven. Elytra exposing abdominal segments 
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBFFFDDFABFC8DC2DC4F9D4" box="[1383,1431,1514,1540]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="7.6">7, 6</number>
, and part of 
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBFFFDDFEC5CB24297DF9FC" box="[285,302,1554,1580]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="5.0">5</number>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB8369BFFBFFFDDFF1ECB0C2BBDF984" blockId="21.[151,1437,634,2020]" box="[198,1006,1594,1620]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Tarsomeres 
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBFFFDDFE8CCB0C29D2F984" box="[340,385,1594,1620]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1–3</number>
with ventral lobes progressively dilated and bilobed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB8369BFFBFFFDDFF1ECB542C49F8CC" blockId="21.[151,1437,634,2020]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Male pygidium shallowly and broadly or narrowly emarginated to broadly rounded, angles rounded. Anal sclerite broadly rounded, truncate, or shallowly emarginate with angles rounded. Perisac length and form variable, from depressed and sub parallel to narrow proximally with distal 
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBFFFDDFC3BCB842BBEF91C" box="[995,1005,1714,1740]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBFFFDDFC20CB842C55F91C" box="[1016,1030,1714,1740]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="3.0">3</number>
– 
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBFFFDDFBCFCB842C72F91C" box="[1047,1057,1714,1740]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBFFFDDFBF4CB842C6FF91C" box="[1068,1084,1714,1740]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="4.0">4</number>
expanded; flagellum reduced proximad of junction with sperm duct, flattened and truncate at proximal apex. Female pygidium broadly rounded; gonocoxae elongate. Basal ring of spermatheca weakly sclerotized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31D6510FFBFFFDEFF1ECA1D290FFCE2" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8BB8369BFFBFFFDEFF1ECA1D2B82FE22" blockId="21.[151,1437,634,2020]" lastBlockId="22.[151,1437,152,898]" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBFFFDDFF1ECA1D29A3F894" box="[198,496,1835,1860]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBFFFDDFF1ECA1D29C8F894" box="[198,411,1835,1860]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sensu">
Orthostolus 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24057F2FFBFFFDDFE82CA1D29C8F894" box="[346,411,1835,1860]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" sensu="stricto">sensu</taxonomicNameLabel>
</taxonomicName>
stricto
</emphasis>
is distributed on Kauai, Oahu, and Maui Nui and contains four described and five undescribed species. 
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBFFFDDFE15CA652A88F8BC" box="[461,731,1875,1900]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBFFFDDFE15CA652AF1F8BC" box="[461,674,1875,1900]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sensu">
Orthostolus 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24057F2FFBFFFDDFDB9CA652AF1F8BC" box="[609,674,1875,1900]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" sensu="lato">sensu</taxonomicNameLabel>
</taxonomicName>
lato
</emphasis>
includes 
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBFFFDDFC89CA642B3DF8BC" box="[849,878,1874,1900]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="14.0">14</number>
species from all of the high islands (
<bibRefCitation id="EF964B6AFFBFFFDDFAEDCA642945F844" author="Sharp" pageId="21" pageNumber="28" refString="Sharp, D. &amp; Scott, H. (1908) Coleoptera 3. In: D. Sharp (Ed.), Fauna Hawaiiensis: being the land-fauna of the Hawaiian Islands. Cambridge University Press, London, pp. 435 - 508." type="book chapter" year="1908">
Sharp &amp; Scott 
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBFFFDDFF02CA4C2945F844" box="[218,278,1914,1940]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="1908.0">1908</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) though five described taxa are herein moved to the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBFFFDDFC1DCA4D2C1FF844" box="[965,1100,1915,1940]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Apetasimus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBFFFDDFC1DCA4D2C1FF844" box="[965,1100,1915,1940]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Apetasimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The taxonomy of 
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBFFFDDFAF2CA4D2898F86C" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBFFFDDFAF2CA4D28EAF86C" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">Orthostolus</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24057F2FFBFFFDDFF18CA952898F86C" box="[192,203,1955,1980]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" sensu="stricto">s</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBFFFDDFF0BCA95288DF86C" box="[211,222,1955,1980]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">s</emphasis>
. is in need of revision and examination of the male genitalia suggests there are two lineages with plesiomorphic, undescribed species on Kauai, each of which has colonized Oahu, Molokai, and Maui, with one lineage also present on Lanai. On East Maui three species can be collected sympatrically within a single stick, and dissection of male genitalia is required to distinguish them. Two of these species are present on West Maui. Two species were described from Oahu, 
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBCFFDEFD0CCDDE2BA8FED2" authority="Sharp" authorityName="Sharp" box="[724,1019,232,258]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nepos">
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBCFFDEFD0CCDDE2BFEFED1" box="[724,941,232,257]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Orthostolus nepos</emphasis>
Sharp
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBCFFDEFBE2CDDE2DCBFED2" authority="Sharp" authorityName="Sharp" box="[1082,1432,232,258]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBCFFDEFBE2CDDE2D60FED1" box="[1082,1331,232,257]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Orthostolus robustus</emphasis>
(Sharp)
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBCFFDEFF4FCC2629DEFEF9" box="[151,397,272,297]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBCFFDEFF4FCC2629DEFEF9" box="[151,397,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Orthostolus robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found in both the Waianae and Koolau Mts. on Oahu and specimens from Lanai were included in the 
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBCFFDEFE8DCC0E2A6EFE81" box="[341,573,312,337]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Fauna 
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBCFFDEFE74CC0E2A6EFE81" box="[428,573,312,337]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Eupetinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hawaiiensis">Hawaiiensis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
redescription (
<bibRefCitation id="EF964B6AFFBCFFDEFD2BCC0E2BD2FE82" author="Sharp" box="[755,897,312,338]" pageId="22" pageNumber="28" refString="Sharp, D. (1878) On some Nitidulidae from the Hawaiian Islands. Transactions of the Royal Entomological Society London, 26, 127 - 140." type="journal article" year="1878">
Sharp 
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBCFFDEFC9BCC0E2BD2FE82" box="[835,897,312,338]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="1878.0">1878</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EF964B6AFFBCFFDEFC48CC0E2CD5FE82" author="Sharp" box="[912,1158,312,338]" pageId="22" pageNumber="28" refString="Sharp, D. &amp; Scott, H. (1908) Coleoptera 3. In: D. Sharp (Ed.), Fauna Hawaiiensis: being the land-fauna of the Hawaiian Islands. Cambridge University Press, London, pp. 435 - 508." type="book chapter" year="1908">
Sharp &amp; Scott 
<number id="3DCF24BCFFBCFFDEFB9FCC0E2CD5FE82" box="[1095,1158,312,338]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="1908.0">1908</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The Lanai specimens previously considered 
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBCFFDEFE7ECC562A62FEA9" box="[422,561,352,378]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBCFFDEFE7ECC5629E8FEA9" box="[422,443,352,377]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBCFFDEFE15CC562A62FEA9" box="[461,561,352,377]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
represent a distinct species; the male genitalia show it to be allied with 
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBCFFDEFF4FCCBE29B9FE72" authority="Sharp" authorityName="Sharp" box="[151,490,392,418]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="germanus">
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBCFFDEFF4FCCBE29CDFE71" box="[151,414,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Orthostolus germanus</emphasis>
Sharp
</taxonomicName>
of Molokai. 
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBCFFDEFD51CCBE2B33FE71" box="[649,864,392,417]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nepos">
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBCFFDEFD51CCBE2B33FE71" box="[649,864,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Orthostolus nepos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected in the southern Koolau Mts. near Honolulu and is known from four male and one female specimen. Based on external morphology they appear to be allied with 
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBCFFDEFE84CCEE29A1FE21" box="[348,498,472,498]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="germanus">
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBCFFDEFE84CCEE2922FE21" box="[348,369,472,497]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBCFFDEFEA7CCEE29A1FE21" box="[383,498,472,497]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">germanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the Lanai specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBCFFDEFC9ACCEE2B99FE21" box="[834,970,472,498]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBCFFDEFC9ACCEE2B04FE21" box="[834,855,472,497]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBCFFDEFCBECCEE2B99FE21" box="[870,970,472,497]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB8369BFFBCFFDEFF1ECF36290FFCE2" blockId="22.[151,1437,152,898]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
All species of 
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBCFFDEFEA8CF362A5EFDC9" box="[368,525,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBCFFDEFEA8CF3629A8FDC9" box="[368,507,512,537]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">Orthostolus</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24057F2FFBCFFDEFDDACF362A5EFDC9" box="[514,525,512,537]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" sensu="stricto">s</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBCFFDEFDCCCF362A4CFDC9" box="[532,543,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">s</emphasis>
. are closely associated with decaying Hawaiian lobelioids in mesic and wet forests. Individuals can be found in actively decaying tissue of stems, droopy leaves, fruit, and flowers. 
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBCFFDEFF4FCF662972FDB9" box="[151,289,592,617]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBCFFDEFF4FCF662972FDB9" box="[151,289,592,617]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Orthostolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are all fully winged and can be collected occasionally on other plants in areas were their hosts occur. They are often very numerous with large numbers of both adults and larvae found together, and often share the substrate with species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBCFFDEFD9CCF962AEAFD69" box="[580,697,672,697]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Eupetinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBCFFDEFD9CCF962AEAFD69" box="[580,697,672,697]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Eupetinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, especially 
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBCFFDEFC94CF962C18FD6A" authority="Sharp" authorityName="Sharp" box="[844,1099,672,698]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Eupetinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="impressus">
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBCFFDEFC94CF962B0DFD69" box="[844,862,672,697]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBCFFDEFCA9CF962BB6FD69" box="[881,997,672,697]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">impressus</emphasis>
(Sharp)
</taxonomicName>
. The species exhibit a high degree of intraspecific variability that overlaps that of other closely related species. They are variable in dorsal microsculpture, punctation, evenness of the surface, coloration, and the degree of sinuation at the hind angle of the pronotum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31D6510FFBCFFDEFF1ECE762D20FC52" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BB8369BFFBCFFDEFF1ECE762D20FC52" blockId="22.[151,1437,152,898]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBCFFDEFF1ECE762903FC89" box="[198,336,832,857]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Orthostolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBCFFDEFF1ECE762903FC89" box="[198,336,832,857]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Orthostolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C074D18FFBCFFDEFE32CE762ADEFC89" box="[490,653,832,857]" class="Insecta" family="Nitidulidae" genus="Cillaeopeplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B973EA89FFBCFFDEFE32CE762ADEFC89" box="[490,653,832,857]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Cillaeopeplus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ecologically and exhibits the same biogeographic pattern of speciation primarily through colonization from older to younger islands with little within-island differentiation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
